            <div style="height: 861px; width: 814px;  height: 861px; left: 118px; position: absolute; top: 1261px; width: 814px; z-index: 1; " class="tinyText style_SkipStrokeSkipFillSkipOpacity">
              <div style="position: relative; width: 814px; ">
                <img src="Autocalls_files/shapeimage_4.png" alt="Vega Behavior&#10;&#10;Below the barrier again 1 day before expiry the trader (or investor in this case) will prefer a low volatility near the barrier. So increasing the volatility below the barrier will increase the probability of structuring ending up the barrier and hence a payout. So price increases due to increasing volatility, Thus Long Vega. &#10;&#10;Above the barrier for volatility increase price decreases. Once I have crossed the hump I would prefer low volatility to avoid the crossover back to below barrier levels. Hence Short vega above the barrier. &#10;&#10;So I am Long vega below the barrier and Short vega above the barrier&#10;&#10;When I am long vega it seems I am long gamma and when I am short vega it I am short gamma.&#10;&#10;Long Vega &amp; Long Gamma: (Below the barrier)&#10;&#10;As spot increases the structure gets Longer  vega and then changes to Short Vega. After the barrier has passed Vega again decreases. This is natural as above the barrier say at 150 and 1 day before expiry naturally volatility can’t have any affect. It’s all delta play. &#10;&#10;Short Vega &amp; Short Gamma: (Above the barrier)&#10;&#10;As spot increases the structure gets Shorter vega for some time but again this affect decreases for higher spot levels as explained above. &#10;&#10;As a trader if I am selling then it’s opposite, I am Short Vega and Short Gamma (below barrier)&#10;Long Vega &amp; Long Gamma above barrier&#10;&#10;Hedging it using vanilla options can be done using....&#10;&#10; &#10;At spot levels of 90 structure is clearly Short Gamma, so let’s buy a put for Long gamma at around 90 strike. I sell a 95 strike put so it will contribute to Short Vega. Combining these two into a put spread let’s see the behavior&#10;           At 90 levels we have Short gamma hedged by 90 strike put (Buy). It will have higher gamma than 95 strike put, coz gamma is highest when spot is closer to the strike.  &#10;&#10;Vega of OTM options is higher than ATM. So buy adjusting the strikes we can generate a positive vega and hedge the negative vega below the barrier. &#10;&#10;Hence with adjusted strikes we can have a hedge with a putspread. Problem is like delta hedging you need to shift the strikes depending on the stability of the hedge. &#10;&#10;" style="height: 802px; left: 0px; margin-left: 2px; margin-top: 7px; position: absolute; top: 0px; width: 806px; " />
              </div>
            </div>
            


            <div style="height: 100px; width: 100px;  height: 100px; left: 14px; position: absolute; top: 1239px; width: 100px; z-index: 1; " class="tinyText">
              <div style="position: relative; width: 100px; ">
                <img src="Autocalls_files/shapeimage_5.png" alt="" style="height: 100px; left: 0px; position: absolute; top: 0px; width: 100px; " />
              </div>
            </div>
            


            <div id="id6" style="height: 218px; left: 120px; position: absolute; top: 2172px; width: 820px; z-index: 1; " class="style_SkipStroke_1 shape-with-text">
              <div class="text-content graphic_textbox_layout_style_default_External_820_218" style="padding: 0px; ">
                <div class="graphic_textbox_layout_style_default">
                  <p style="padding-top: 0pt; " class="paragraph_style_8">Rebalancing<br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style_8"><br /></p>
                  <p style="padding-bottom: 0pt; " class="paragraph_style">A question might be asked, why choose a putspread and not a callspread. Well putspread is cheaper since calls are ITM. Still as spot/time moves the peak of vega/gamma will keep shifting. As expiry approaches basically both peaks approach the barrier. So with this shifting, it requires our hedge to be shifted. Shifting upwards the put spread is ok, coz you make gains as the high strike short put makes money. Shifting downwards will register losses. The structure price allthough decreases and should make up for the losses in hedge, but if volatility is low the hedge hedge will have greater losses. Hedge was long gamma in the lower portion. Hedge will lose theta, and gamma won’t be able to make up for it due to lower volatility. Theta is the time effect, and it is loss of option value due to passage of time. Generally known as “RENT” paid by the option owner. </p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            


            <div id="id7" style="height: 492px; left: 118px; position: absolute; top: 2422px; width: 814px; z-index: 1; " class="style_SkipStroke_1 shape-with-text">
              <div class="text-content graphic_textbox_layout_style_default_External_814_492" style="padding: 0px; ">
                <div class="graphic_textbox_layout_style_default">
                  <p style="padding-top: 0pt; " class="paragraph_style_9">Introducing Vol of Vol<br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style_8"><br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style">Vol of vol as it says denotes volatility of volatility. If it’s high it simply means that volatility can cover a large range in a few days. If it’s low it means volatility is stable and doesn’t change much. So if volatility is high, trader will prefer a low vol of vol in long gamma range. High volatility of volatility might lead to losses in long gamma region. <br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style">Another issue is hedging, which till date I haven’t come across a hedge using vanilla’s for price changes in exotics due to vol of vol. This in-fact is the second derivative of structure price with sigma. Derivatives of the payoff which above a specific spot is positive and below that specific spot 0 (assume 1 day before expiry and spot at 109 for barrier 110), has very high sensitivity to volatility. A put spread of exactly the same expiry will replicate this behavior, but practically the put spread of same expiry might not be available in the market. <br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style">Another issue is that strikes are in steps of 10 or 20 or 100, but for replicating a specific barrier point we need very close strikes so it is just an approximation and can’t work at expiry. <br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style">One of the solutions generally used by traders is to simulate these greeks 5 - 10 days before expiry. These are priced into the structure. Another question might be why not use the heston model which automatically prices these greeks?<br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style">Problem with heston is that it assumes daily hedging and as usual the probability of the worst case happening is very low. Heston model or any other model is generating paths and averaging out the price for each of these paths. For traders an average case might not be a suitable answer to the manager - “Hey I made a loss, in one of the structures but rest assured out of 100, 60 will make money!”. <br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
